<speak version="1.0" xml:lang="en-US" xmlns:mstts="http://www.w3.org/2001/mstts">
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="-10%" pitch="+0st">
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S1"/> Cells are the building blocks of life.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S2"/> They play a crucial role in all living organisms.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S3"/> Without cells, life as we know it would not exist.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S4"/> Let's explore what makes cells so important.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S5"/> A cell is the smallest unit of life that can function independently.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S6"/> Cells are responsible for carrying out essential processes.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S7"/> we have two main types of cells: prokaryotic and eukaryotic.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S8"/> Prokaryotic cells are simpler and lack a nucleus.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S9"/> Eukaryotic cells are more complex and have a defined nucleus.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S10"/> Think of prokaryotes as the basic models and eukaryotes as the advanced versions.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S11"/> Both types of cells perform vital functions like energy production and reproduction.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S12"/> A common pitfall is confusing the two types of cells.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S13"/> Remember, prokaryotes are simpler and do not have membrane-bound organelles.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S14"/> Let's do a quick check.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S15"/> Can you name one function of a cell?</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S16"/> Cells can produce energy, grow, and respond to their environment.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S17"/> In recap, cells are essential for life, and they come in two main types.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S18"/> Understanding cells is the first step in studying biology.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
    </prosody>
  </voice></speak>